504. Base 7
Given an integer num, return a string of its base 7 representation.

Example 1:
Input: num = 100
Output: "202"

Example 2:
Input: num = -7
Output: "-10"


class Solution {
    public String convertToBase7(int num) {
        if (num == 0) return "0";
        boolean negative = num < 0;
        num = Math.abs(num);
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        while (num > 0) {
            sb.append(num % 7);
            num /= 7;
        }
        if (negative) 
            sb.append("-");
        return sb.reverse().toString();
    }
}


TC: O(log⁡∣num∣)
SC: O(log⁡∣num∣)


🔹 Time Complexity
We repeatedly divide num by 7 until it becomes 0.
Each division produces one digit in base 7.
So, the number of iterations = number of digits in base 7.
🔹 How many digits in base 7?
The number of digits of a number n in base b is about:
⌊log⁡b(n)⌋+1
So for base 7:
digits≈log⁡7(n)
Each loop iteration is O(1) (just division and modulus).
Total iterations = log⁡7(n).
Therefore:
TC=O(log⁡7(n))(which is equivalent to O(log⁡n) in Big-O notation)
